Description: CVE-2026-12087 - Fix out-of-bounds read in pack_ip_mreq_source()
 The Socket XS function pack_ip_mreq_source() reused the STRLEN len
 variable from the multiaddr argument when validating the source
 argument, allowing a too-short source to pass the length check and
 causing a fixed-size copy to read past the end of the buffer.
 Use a separate length for the source argument and validate it after
 reading the source bytes, matching the upstream Socket 2.041 fix.
 .
 This is a minimal, targeted backport of the security fix only; the
 unrelated Pod documentation reformatting and version bump from the
 upstream 2.041 release are not included.
 .
 Context adapted for Perl 5.32.1 (Debian bullseye): Socket.xs uses
 tabs and multi-line croak format strings. STRLEN sourcelen is declared
 at the top of the new block (C89 / -Werror=declaration-after-statement).
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/Perl/perl5/commit/de19a0b0ad1900fef976c5c1400bd8f11ec6c6cb
Bug: https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2026-12087
Author: Paul Evans <leonerd@leonerd.org.uk>
Last-Update: 2026-07-17
---
--- a/cpan/Socket/Socket.xs
+++ b/cpan/Socket/Socket.xs
@@ -1310,13 +1310,16 @@ pack_ip_mreq_source(multiaddr, source, interface=&PL_sv_undef)
 		croak("Bad arg length %s, length is %" UVuf
                       ", should be %" UVuf,
 		      "Socket::pack_ip_mreq", (UV)len, (UV)sizeof(mreq.imr_multiaddr));
-	if (DO_UTF8(source) && !sv_utf8_downgrade(source, 1))
-		croak("Wide character in %s", "Socket::pack_ip_mreq_source");
-	if (len != sizeof(mreq.imr_sourceaddr))
-		croak("Bad arg length %s, length is %" UVuf
+	{
+		STRLEN sourcelen;
+		if (DO_UTF8(source) && !sv_utf8_downgrade(source, 1))
+			croak("Wide character in %s", "Socket::pack_ip_mreq_source");
+		sourcebytes = SvPVbyte(source, sourcelen);
+		if (sourcelen != sizeof(mreq.imr_sourceaddr))
+			croak("Bad arg length %s, length is %" UVuf
                       ", should be %" UVuf,
-		      "Socket::pack_ip_mreq", (UV)len, (UV)sizeof(mreq.imr_sourceaddr));
-	sourcebytes = SvPVbyte(source, len);
+			      "Socket::pack_ip_mreq", (UV)sourcelen, (UV)sizeof(mreq.imr_sourceaddr));
+	}
 	Zero(&mreq, sizeof(mreq), char);
 	Copy(multiaddrbytes, &mreq.imr_multiaddr, sizeof(mreq.imr_multiaddr), char);
 	Copy(sourcebytes, &mreq.imr_sourceaddr, sizeof(mreq.imr_sourceaddr), char);
Description: Fix CVE-2026-48959 - algorithmic-complexity DoS in IO::Uncompress::Unzip::fastForward
 IO::Uncompress::Unzip versions before 2.220 contain a typo in the
 fastForward() chunk-size clamp: the code applies Perl's length() operator
 to the integer $offset, which stringifies it and yields its digit count
 (1-19) rather than the offset value itself. The comparison
 "length $offset < $c" therefore evaluates to true on every iteration of
 the loop, collapsing the per-iteration read from 16 KiB down to 1-19
 bytes. When a named entry is extracted from an attacker-controlled zip
 archive via IO::Uncompress::Unzip->new($zip, Name => $target), the loop
 scales linearly with the entry's compressed size (up to ~4 GiB for
 non-Zip64 archives), causing CPU exhaustion / DoS (CWE-407).
 .
 The fix removes the spurious length() calls so the chunk-size clamp
 compares the remaining offset to the current chunk size, preserving the
 intended 16 KiB chunk reads and only shrinking the chunk on the loop's
 tail iteration.
 .
 This patch is the verbatim upstream IO-Compress 2.220 fix
 (commit 68db44076f4c1a86a2ffe53a958eac6cabaf72e2) backported to the
 IO-Compress 2.093 copy bundled in perl 5.32.1. The surrounding code in
 fastForward() is byte-identical between 2.093 and 2.220, so no
 contextual adjustment is required.
Origin: backport, https://github.com/pmqs/IO-Compress/commit/68db44076f4c1a86a2ffe53a958eac6cabaf72e2
Bug: https://github.com/pmqs/IO-Compress/issues/72
Bug-Debian: https://bugs.debian.org/1138856
Forwarded: not-needed
Author: Root.io Novel Patcher <security@root.io>
Last-Update: 2026-06-10

