Description: CVE-2026-7010 - Validate control characters in Request-URI and Method
 HTTP::Tiny did not validate the request URI or HTTP method for control
 characters before writing the request line, allowing CRLF/control-character
 injection that could be used for request smuggling or header injection
 attacks when the URI or method is attacker-influenced (e.g. user-supplied
 URLs to a webhook/fetch endpoint).
 .
 Backported from upstream HTTP-Tiny commit
 d73c7651e82ace02693842df55928b6c3ae7c38d (released as HTTP-Tiny 0.093).
 Only the write_request_header hunk is applied; the write_header_lines
 Field_Content validation hunk from the same upstream commit is already
 present in the bundled HTTP-Tiny 0.076 shipped with Debian bullseye perl
 5.32.1-4+deb11u5 and is therefore omitted.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/Perl-Toolchain-Gang/HTTP-Tiny/commit/d73c7651e82ace02693842df55928b6c3ae7c38d
Author: Stig <stig@stig.io>
Last-Update: 2026-07-17
---
--- a/cpan/HTTP-Tiny/lib/HTTP/Tiny.pm
+++ b/cpan/HTTP-Tiny/lib/HTTP/Tiny.pm
@@ -1513,6 +1513,12 @@ sub write_request_header {
     @_ == 5 || die(q/Usage: $handle->write_request_header(method, request_uri, headers, header_case)/ . "\n");
     my ($self, $method, $request_uri, $headers, $header_case) = @_;
 
+    die (q/Invalid characters in Request-URI /. $Printable->($request_uri). "\n")
+      if $request_uri =~ /[\x00-\x20\x7F]/;
+
+    die (q/Invalid characters in Method /. $Printable->($method). "\n")
+      if $method =~ /[\x00-\x20\x7F]/;
+
     return $self->write_header_lines($headers, $header_case, "$method $request_uri HTTP/1.1\x0D\x0A");
 }
Description: CVE-2026-13221 - Fix integer overflow in regex trie compilation
 Perl_study_chunk (regcomp.c, S_study_chunk in this pre-split version) could
 build a trie from a branch sequence whose delta (tail - startbranch) exceeds
 the 16-bit field used to store it, causing silently incorrect regex match
 results for alternations of more than 65535 fixed-string branches. Skip the
 trie optimization when this delta would overflow.
 .
 This is a manual backport/re-homing of the upstream commit: upstream had
 already split regcomp.c into regcomp_study.c, so the guard is applied here to
 the equivalent inline logic in the monolithic regcomp.c (S_study_chunk). The
 regression test is added to t/re/pat_advanced.t at the equivalent location
 before the crash-test NOTE section.
Origin: backport, upstream commit:03f74bbbd3a68350d926ee93d56ee4808c28c4c7
Author: Karl Williamson <khw@cpan.org>
Last-Update: 2026-07-17
---
--- a/regcomp.c
+++ b/regcomp.c
@@ -4914,6 +4914,17 @@
                         }
 
 
+                        /* The code below currently saves the difference from
+                         * start to finish in a 16-bit field, causing
+                         * GH #23388.  This defeats the design of batching
+                         * tries into chunks that each fit.  khw thinks it is
+                         * too late in the 5.44 cycle to relook at the design,
+                         * so for now anyway, don't make a trie that would
+                         * overflow */
+                        if (tail - startbranch >= U16_MAX) {
+                            continue;
+                        }
+
                         DEBUG_TRIE_COMPILE_r({
                             regprop(RExC_rx, RExC_mysv, tail, NULL, pRExC_state);
                             Perl_re_indentf( aTHX_  "%s %" UVuf ":%s\n",
--- a/t/re/pat_advanced.t
+++ b/t/re/pat_advanced.t
@@ -2585,6 +2585,15 @@
     }
 
 
+    { # GH #23388
+        fresh_perl_is(<<~'PROG', , "", {}, "Avoid trie overflow");
+            my $x = join "|", "aaa".."mzz";
+            my $y = join "|", "naa".."zzz";
+            use re 'Debug';
+            "fnord" =~ m/(?:$x)|(?:$y)/;
+            PROG
+    }
+
     # !!! NOTE that tests that aren't at all likely to crash perl should go
     # a ways above, above these last ones.  There's a comment there that, like
     # this comment, contains the word 'NOTE'
Description: Fix CVE-2026-9538 - cap entry size during read in Archive::Tar
 The tar header's 12-byte size field is attacker-controlled. Archive::Tar's
 non-skip extract path in _read_tar allocates a Perl scalar of the declared
 size before returning the read-short error, allowing a few-KB compressed
 archive declaring a 100 GB inner entry to trigger immediate multi-GB
 allocation.
 .
 Add $MAX_FILE_SIZE (default 1 GiB) checked once per entry inside
 _read_tar, gating both the chunked-skip and full-slurp branches. Set to
 0 to disable the cap.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/jib/archive-tar-new/commit/f9af01426038e29d9578825a0cd3626946ab08c7
Author: Stig Palmquist <stig@stig.io>
Last-Update: 2026-05-27

---
--- a/cpan/Archive-Tar/lib/Archive/Tar.pm
+++ b/cpan/Archive-Tar/lib/Archive/Tar.pm
@@ -24,6 +24,7 @@ use strict;
 use vars qw[$DEBUG $error $VERSION $WARN $FOLLOW_SYMLINK $CHOWN $CHMOD
             $DO_NOT_USE_PREFIX $HAS_PERLIO $HAS_IO_STRING $SAME_PERMISSIONS
             $INSECURE_EXTRACT_MODE $ZERO_PAD_NUMBERS @ISA @EXPORT $RESOLVE_SYMLINK
+            $MAX_FILE_SIZE
          ];

 @ISA                    = qw[Exporter];
@@ -39,6 +40,7 @@ $DO_NOT_USE_PREFIX      = 0;
 $INSECURE_EXTRACT_MODE  = 0;
 $ZERO_PAD_NUMBERS       = 0;
 $RESOLVE_SYMLINK        = $ENV{'PERL5_AT_RESOLVE_SYMLINK'} || 'speed';
+$MAX_FILE_SIZE          = 1024 * 1024 * 1024;

 BEGIN {
     use Config;
@@ -442,6 +444,14 @@ sub _read_tar {

             my $block = BLOCK_SIZE->( $entry->size );

+            if ( $MAX_FILE_SIZE && $entry->size > $MAX_FILE_SIZE ) {
+                $self->_error( qq[Entry '] . $entry->full_path .
+                    qq[' declared size ] . $entry->size .
+                    qq[ bytes exceeds \$Archive::Tar::MAX_FILE_SIZE ] .
+                    qq[($MAX_FILE_SIZE); refusing to allocate] );
+                next LOOP;
+            }
+
             $data = $entry->get_content_by_ref;

 	    my $skip = 0;
@@ -2141,6 +2151,13 @@ zero padded numbers for C<size>, C<mtime>
 The default is C<0>, indicating that we will create space padded
 numbers. Added for compatibility with C<busybox> implementations.

+=head2 $Archive::Tar::MAX_FILE_SIZE
+
+This variable holds an upper bound on the per-entry declared size that
+C<Archive::Tar> will accept when reading an archive. Entries whose header
+claims a larger size are refused with an error before any read allocation.
+Defaults to 1 GiB. Set to 0 to disable the cap.
+
 =head2 Tuning the way RESOLVE_SYMLINK will works

 	You can tune the behaviour by setting the $Archive::Tar::RESOLVE_SYMLINK variable,
